title: Kazuchika Okada vs Kenny Omega
background:
Kenny Omega earned the title shot by winning the 2016 G1 Climax, becoming the first non-Japanese winner of that tournament's modern era and securing the right to challenge for the IWGP Heavyweight Championship. Kazuchika Okada entered Wrestle Kingdom 11 as the reigning IWGP Heavyweight Champion, established as NJPW's top star after a dominant run that included multiple high-profile title defenses.
The rivalry was fueled by factional tensions, Omega as a leading figure in Bullet Club and Okada as the centerpiece of CHAOS, which produced repeated confrontations in multi-man matches, tag bouts, and promotional segments throughout late 2016. Those encounters sharpened the personal stakes: Omega's aggressive, boundary-pushing style and Okada's composed, championship-level psychology created a clear contrast that promoters and fans framed as a generational and stylistic clash.
Promos and in-ring moments in the months before January amplified anticipation. Omega's G1 victory gave him momentum and legitimacy; Okada's long title reign and status as NJPW's “ace” made the match a test of whether a new international star could unseat the company's established leader.
spoiler:
Okada retained the IWGP Heavyweight Championship at Wrestle Kingdom 11, but the match's immediate aftermath was to intensify and extend the Okada-Omega rivalry, elevate Kenny Omega's international profile, and set up a string of high-stakes rematches that became one of modern NJPW's defining series.
The match was widely praised by fans and critics for its pacing, dramatic near-falls, and sustained intensity, and it immediately boosted Kenny Omega's standing as a legitimate main-event star while reinforcing Kazuchika Okada's status as NJPW's top champion. The Tokyo Dome main event drew attention beyond Japan, helping NJPW reach a broader international audience and increasing demand for further encounters between the two men.
Promoters capitalized on the rivalry: ticket demand and international interest increased for shows featuring either man, and the series helped NJPW expand its global footprint through streaming and media coverage. For Omega, the sustained spotlight contributed to his eventual status as a global star beyond NJPW; for Okada, the matches reinforced his role as the company's “ace” and a performer capable of carrying multi-match sagas.
The WK11 bout did not settle the rivalry; instead it served as the opening chapter of a multi-match saga that culminated in further classics and a title change later in the series, cementing both wrestlers' reputations and influencing booking approaches to long-term rivalries in modern pro wrestling.

title: Bret Hart vs Steve Austin
background:
The match at WrestleMania 13 grew from Steve Austin's rapid rise in 1996 and Bret Hart's position as a veteran standard-bearer for the company. Throughout late 1996 and early 1997 Austin's increasingly aggressive, anti-authority persona and hard-hitting style made him a breakout star, while Hart remained one of the promotion's most respected in-ring technicians and storytellers. Promos, brawls, and encounters on television and at house shows escalated the personal stakes between the two: Austin's relentless, no-nonsense approach clashed with Hart's cerebral, submission-based psychology. The match was framed as a decisive, violent confrontation between a new, volatile star and an established master of the ring.

WrestleMania 13’s stipulation — a No Disqualification Submission match — amplified the brutality and allowed both men to push physical limits. The build emphasized toughness, pride, and the idea that only one man could impose his will. In the weeks leading to the event, Austin’s willingness to brawl and take punishment contrasted with Hart’s methodical ring craft, creating a narrative that the match would be both a physical brawl and a psychological chess match. That tension set the stage for a contest remembered for its intensity, blood, and dramatic finish.
spoiler: The match is widely remembered for the double turn: Hart’s technical, principled persona hardened into a heel, while Austin’s bloodied, defiant performance converted crowd sympathy into sustained babyface momentum. Bret Hart leaned into a more bitter, cerebral heel presentation that influenced his promos and booking; Steve Austin’s image as a rebellious, anti‑authority figure became the centerpiece of WWF storytelling and merchandising going forward. The bout’s storytelling techniques, selling, and crowd psychology became a template for future marquee matches. Wrestling shifted toward character‑driven, reality‑tinged narratives, and Austin’s mainstream appeal helped WWF capitalize on that shift commercially and culturally.

title: Kazuchika Okada vs Kenny Omega
background:
Dominion 2018’s Okada vs. Omega arrived as the climactic chapter of a multi‑year rivalry, built on escalating stakes, contrasting styles, and a narrative of mutual obsession that set the stage for an ultra‑long, emotionally charged main event.

Okada and Omega had been trading high‑profile matches since Wrestle Kingdom 11, with each encounter raising the stakes and deepening the storyline between NJPW’s established ace and its foreign challenger.

Their feud evolved from athletic competition into a layered saga about legacy, pride, and the quest to be the company’s definitive top star.

The match was presented with no time limit and a multi‑fall structure, signaling that both men would be given room to tell a long, evolving story in the ring.
spoiler:
The Okada–Omega series, culminating at Dominion, proved that multi‑match, long‑form storytelling could sustain international interest and media coverage, encouraging promoters to build extended arcs rather than one‑off spectacles. NJPW’s international profile rose as the match drew attention outside Japan, prompting greater focus on global streaming, English commentary, and cross‑border talent narratives.

Omega’s ascent validated the idea that non‑Japanese stars could carry NJPW’s top title and helped normalize international main‑event pushes. 

 Dominion 2018 didn’t just crown a new champion — it validated a model of long‑form, character‑driven main events that reshaped booking priorities and accelerated NJPW’s global ambitions, with ripple effects felt across the wrestling business.

title: Kazuchika Okada (c) vs Katsuyori Shibata
background:
Kazuchika Okada defended the IWGP Heavyweight Championship against Katsuyori Shibata at Sakura Genesis on 9 April 2017, a match born from Shibata’s surprise New Japan Cup victory and a long‑building contrast between Okada’s polished “ace” psychology and Shibata’s hard‑hitting strong‑style intensity.

 The match was promoted as a test of whether Shibata’s raw intensity could overcome Okada’s championship craft, and many viewers expected a hard‑hitting, short‑to‑medium length bout rather than a drawn‑out classic

Commentary and early reviews framed the encounter as one of the most eagerly awaited title defenses of 2017, with observers noting the potential for a career‑defining performance from Shibata and a chance for Okada to reaffirm his status.
spoiler:
The bout at Sakura Genesis 2017 left an immediate, stark legacy: Shibata collapsed after a shoot‑style headbutt, later diagnosed with a subdural hematoma, a life‑threatening brain bleed that required urgent medical attention and long recovery. The injury transformed the match from a celebrated strong‑style encounter into a cautionary touchstone about in‑ring risk and the use of unprotected skull‑on‑skull strikes.

Many reviewers hailed the match as one of the most brutal, emotionally raw main events of the 2010s, praising both men’s commitment and the match’s dramatic arc. Commentators and fans debated whether the dangerous spot was necessary, with some calling it an avoidable risk that overshadowed the performance.

In the years after, the match has been revisited as both a career‑defining performance and a sobering example of wrestling’s physical limits; retrospectives emphasize its artistry while acknowledging the human cost and the industry’s responsibility to protect performers. Shibata’s in‑ring future was uncertain for a long time, and the bout remains a frequent reference point in conversations about safety, booking, and the ethics of “strong style” presentation.

title: Kazuchika Okada (c) vs Kenny Omega
background:
The match was booked as a direct rematch from earlier encounters in 2017, part of a trilogy that carried heavy narrative weight after their January encounters; Dominion 6.11 in Osaka‑jō Hall served as NJPW’s biggest show between Wrestle Kingdom and the G1 Climax, and the card leaned on those continuing storylines to sell the main event. Omega entered as the international, boundary‑pushing challenger whose 2016–17 run had elevated him into true main‑event status, while Okada remained the company’s long‑reigning IWGP Heavyweight Champion and narrative center, making the bout a classic established‑champion vs. ascendant‑outsider confrontation

Promos and prior matches emphasized contrasting styles, Okada’s championship psychology and Rainmaker theatrics against Omega’s inventive offense and willingness to push rules and pacing, which created a sense that Dominion could either settle the rivalry or extend it depending on finish and crowd reaction. The match was promoted and discussed as a potential all‑time classic, with many fans expecting a long, dramatic encounter rather than a short flurry; that framing shaped both in‑ring pacing and audience expectations.
spoiler:
The main event finished as a 60‑minute time‑limit draw, leaving the IWGP Heavyweight picture unresolved and the Osaka‑jō Hall crowd of ~11,756 buzzing about the parity between the two stars. Critics hailed the match for its sustained drama, pacing, and unpredictability; many reviews placed it among the year’s best and argued it cemented the Okada–Omega series as one of modern wrestling’s defining rivalries.

Dominion reinforced NJPW’s global standing as a promotion producing long, athletic, and narratively rich main events, helping attract international attention and streaming viewership for subsequent cards. The unresolved finish deliberately extended the storyline, demonstrating NJPW’s appetite for multi‑match sagas and influencing how promotions present long‑term rivalries and time‑limit drama.

title: Kenny Omega (c) vs Will Ospreay
background:
The build to Omega vs Ospreay at Forbidden Door 2023 leaned heavily on history and contrast. Promoters and commentators framed the match as a continuation of a rivalry defined by innovation and escalation: Omega’s cinematic, psychology‑driven offense versus Ospreay’s aerial dynamism and increasingly hard‑edged repertoire. Both men had accumulated marquee wins and high‑profile matches across NJPW and AEW, so the rematch carried the implicit question of who could adapt and close the chapter.

The match was positioned to test in‑ring evolution (who had added new counters, who could sustain a long, dramatic main event) and to serve as a barometer for AEW×NJPW collaboration quality. Fans expected a blend of athletic spectacle and narrative payoff; critics were ready to evaluate whether the bout advanced the rivalry or merely replayed familiar beats.
spoiler:
Reviewers called the match an instant classic, praising its pacing, near‑falls, and dramatic escalation; many outlets placed it among the show’s best matches and a contender for match‑of‑the‑year. Social media and backstage reports described an enthusiastic reception, with peers and staff reportedly congratulating both men for a performance that stole the show on a stacked card

The match reinforced Forbidden Door as a must‑see cross‑promotion event, demonstrating the drawing power of inter‑promotion dream matches and boosting interest in future AEW×NJPW cards.

title: Shawn Michaels vs The Undertaker
background:
The culmination of a long, personal rivalry and months of careful storytelling that pitched Michaels’ comeback‑era bravado against Undertaker’s mythic WrestleMania streak; the match was promoted as a generational, career‑defining encounter.

Shawn Michaels and The Undertaker carried a layered history into WrestleMania 25: two previous WrestleMania classics (including a 2007 encounter) had already established a deep in‑ring chemistry and mutual respect, and both men were positioned as marquee attractions for WWE’s 25th anniversary show. The build emphasized personal stakes and legacy rather than belts. Promos and vignettes framed Michaels as the consummate performer who had repeatedly returned from retirement to chase perfection, while Undertaker was cast as the immovable force protecting his WrestleMania mystique. Creative choices, cinematic entrances, intimate backstage segments, and repeated callbacks to past encounters amplified the sense that this was not just another match but a chapter in a long saga
spoiler: HBK had a swan song like few have had and except for one match has stayed retired. The match is remembered both as a peak creative achievement and as a catalyst that nudged the industry toward more narrative‑driven, emotionally resonant main events; its commercial success and critical acclaim ensured the match would be taught, dissected, and emulated for years.

title: John Cena (c) vs CM Punk
background:
CM Punk’s Money in the Bank 2011 program with John Cena was built around a real‑time contract storyline and Punk’s incendiary promos, most notably the “pipebomb,” which blurred kayfabe and reality and set the stage for Punk’s on‑air ultimatum to leave WWE with the WWE Championship. CM Punk’s character had been cultivated as an outsider and anti‑establishment voice within WWE; his real‑life frustrations and backstage standing were woven into television storytelling. Punk’s momentum accelerated after a series of high‑profile promos and matches that positioned him as a credible top‑card threat to Cena’s mainstream, company‑approved persona. The Money in the Bank build leaned on Punk’s Chicago roots and the idea that a hometown victory could be both a storyline payoff and a genuine career turning point.

Punk’s promos in the months before Money in the Bank, especially the infamous “pipebomb” on Monday Night Raw, used unscripted‑sounding language, direct criticism of WWE management, and references to real backstage dynamics. That promo and subsequent interviews blurred the line between storyline and reality, convincing many viewers that Punk’s grievances were authentic rather than purely scripted. The result was a surge in audience engagement often called the “Summer of Punk,” where chants, social media, and mainstream coverage amplified the angle’s impact. Promos referenced contract dates, creative control, and perceived favoritism in ways that sounded like insider talk; WWE leaned into this ambiguity, allowing fans to debate what was real. That blending made the match feel unpredictable and elevated its cultural footprint beyond typical wrestling storylines.
spoiler:
After defeating John Cena in Chicago, Punk exited the arena with the title, creating a live, unpredictable moment that dominated coverage.

The match’s aftermath elevated CM Punk into a top‑tier, mainstream figure and proved the commercial value of reality‑tinged storytelling; the angle drove social‑media buzz and renewed interest in WWE’s pay‑per‑view product. Promos and segments after the event kept the contract premise front and center, forcing WWE creative to navigate the tension between a believable “walk‑out” and the scripted world of television.
